<Author>maxim531
<Content>Great hotel to chill out - mix of urban chic in the middle of rice paddies Great hotel - but stay at least 2 nights to enjoy it's full flavor. This hotel is great in its attention to the little details and free amenities. Wife and I stayed here during our honeymoon while on our way to Amed for one night. Check in team was very friendly considering our check in time was late in the evening. Security to the hotel was fairly tight given that it's not as large as say, the Ritz Carlton in Jimbaran. I would not necessarily recommend this hotel for the disabled or those in a wheelchair. There are too many stairs between the units to make it easy to move around. Not that very many hotels in Bali are handicapped accessible, but this one didn't appear to be one of the easier ones. Initial reactions were wow! The beds utilize some very large mosquito nets that at night when illuminated give a nice shimmery effect to the room along with the warm accent lighting in the bedrooms. The beds themselves were huge (king), with at least 400 thread count linens, wonderful down comforter, and some of the softest down pillows I've ever rested my head on. I did not upload any pictures because of the way the photos came out. Photos doesn't do this place justice when you take photos of it during the daytime. It's the evening, nighttime vibe with all the wonderful pool and walkway illumination of this place that makes it so cool and tranquil. Someone designed this place to reflect one word: RELAX. Air conditioning units were some of the best I'd experienced during our stay in Bali. This in conjunction with the overhead fan took care of any and all of our cooling needs. I noticed that Uma Ubud actually has their own branded flip flops for you waiting by the bedside when you arrive. Not only were the flip flops very comfortable, they actually left a men's size on one side for me and a smaller women's size on the other side of the bed for my wife. I found this attention to detail most gratifying and surprising. We also received free arrival drinks in addition to a fresh fruit bowl waiting for us in the room, as well as some wonderful fresh flowers in the bathroom. When we got to the room, our outside patio area had two wicker chairs separated by a small table with a glass hurricane and candle. The candle was already lit for our arrival and lent a very warm atmosphere to chill out outside if we chose. Very nice touch.If there's one thing that the Uma Ubud has better than all the other hotels we stayed at (including the Ritz Carlton, Ellie's, Bayu Cottages, and Alam Jiwa) it's that their water pressure and temperature, and bathroom setup is one of the strongest and hottest that I've ever experienced in a hotel room anywhere in the world at this price. Extra long (by U.S. standards) and deep tubs are accompanied with a very cool indoor/outdoor shower feature. I took a walk outside the next morning to figure out how they were able to get such ridiculous water pressure and temperature and noticed that our room potentially shares one industrial sized water boiler with one other room (either that or it was dedicated just for our one room). I've never seen this kind of hot water set up with a hotel room. Incredible.Room was outfitted with a very good electronic room safe for valuables and when you opened the closet doors, they automatically turned on the interior lights of the closet. My wife had picked up a very bad cough and was in our bedroom to sleep it off when I requested cough syrup from the front desk. The front desk immediately gave me 4 cold tablets for my wife and volunteered to take care of the cough syrup request for me. 20 mins later a chime at our room's front door with a smiling serviceman with a bottle of Vicks Formula 44 bought from the local apothecary automatically charged to the room at cost. At nighttime, the illumination details of Uma Ubud are very cool. Free internet PCs (only 2 of them) are available for use w/high speed connection. Given the lack of ability to get decent broadband throughout Bali this was a very nice plus. While my wife was sleeping off the cold, I swung by the restaurant to get some food and drinks. Their Bali coffee was very good as was their summer spring roll appetizers. Highly recommended spring roll sauces!The layout of their restaurant/bar is VERY chill as it overlooks the pool with vanishing edge. It felt more New York lounge than Ubud hotel. Upbeat chill music played in the background while the staff was incredibly hospitable - I was the only one in the bar at the time. One of the cool things about the restaurant/bar is that it's lined with two bookcases that line one of the walkways to the bar that's actually filled with hardcover classics to read. Everything from Herman Melville's Moby Dick to Tolstoi's War and Peace could be found for your reading pleasure. Water features at this hotel were beautiful. The outdoor pool with vanishing edge was unusually cold however - couldn't tell if it was separately chilled by a refrigeration unit or if that was something unique to the climate in Ubud. What makes Uma Ubud great is that amenities you get at this price. Definitely take advantage of the free morning tour (8AM) lasts about 1-1/2 hours through the rice fields. Our guide even provided us mosquito repellent for the walk. Be sure to wear long pants on this walk and decent shoes, I would not recommend flip flops for the tour in that it requires you to traverse some difficult slopes and slippery walkways. Great photo ops and opportunities to ask questions about the local vegetation and customs. The complimentary breakfast buffet the next morning was wonderful. Highly recommend their a la carte menu with Balinese menu items. Great chefs! Breakfast overlooked their koi pond and decorative waterfall. While walking back to our rooms I noticed hotel staff manually conditioning all of the teak wood fixtures in the restaurant/bar/pool area in addition to manually sweeping up all of the fallen frangipani flower buds. They appear to do this every day in that a wet frangipani becomes quite slippery on their stone walkways. Although we only stayed one night, I definitely would have liked to have stayed at least one or two more nights to enjoy all the little things that Uma Ubud had to offer. I will definitely stay at Uma Ubud again when my wife and I revisit Ubud for our future wedding anniversary. 
